The [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Day|Brian Day]] biography is largely uncited and reads like a heroic movie plot.  <small><span class="autosigned">—&nbsp;Preceding [[Wikipedia:Signatures|unsigned]] comment added by [[User:Lenshockington|Lenshockington]] ([[User talk:Lenshockington|talk]] • [[Special:Contributions/Lenshockington|contribs]]) 19:34, 12 May 2014 (UTC)</span></small><!-- Template:Unsigned --> <!--Autosigned by SineBot-->
:[[User:Lenshockington|Lenshockington]], I have tagged [[ Brian Day|the article]] for needing more references and for unencylopedic tone. It would of course be desirable that someone actually fixes the article, but experience unfortunately shows that chances for this to happen is slim. Thanks for notifying. Regards, [[User:Iselilja|Iselilja]] ([[User talk:Iselilja|talk]]) 20:08, 12 May 2014 (UTC)
: I have cleaned the article up a bit, and watchlisted it as well. [[User:Cwobeel|Cwobeel]] ([[User talk:Cwobeel|talk]]) 02:46, 13 May 2014 (UTC)

== Ignazio Ciufolini ==

*{{la|Ignazio Ciufolini}}

A while ago a series of SPAs whose contributions are limited to editing this biography insisted on inserting a "Misconducts" (seriously) section detailing an incident where the subject was accused of using "sockpuppets" to submit papers to [[ArXiv]] critical of his competitors. The original discussion ended with agreement that the source for the controversy was essentially ArXiv itself, which made it inappropriate at best. There were also concerns about [[WP:UNDUE|weight]]. Now there's apparently a new source, a Discover Magazine [http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/neuroskeptic/2014/05/10/pseudonyms-vs-sock-puppets/ blog] that mentions the controversy. My problem with this is that the source is indeed a blog, written by someone under a pseudonym. Which also invites us to peruse other blogs for more information, in addition to the blogs used as secondary sources to re-insert the information. In other words, all this can be sourced only to ArXiv itself or blogs. In my opinion this is not sufficient to justify including it in the subject's biography, especially not by SPAs. But perhaps other BLP-savvy editors disagree. Here is a [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ignazio_Ciufolini&diff=prev&oldid=608272954 relevant diff]. <span style="color:red; font-size: smaller; font-weight: bold;">§[[User:FreeRangeFrog|<span style="color:#00CA00">FreeRangeFrog</span>]]</span><sup>[[User talk:FreeRangeFrog|croak]]</sup> 20:23, 12 May 2014 (UTC)
: Now, the situation is substantially changed because of the appearance of several reliable, independent, third-parties sources<ref name="JASIST 2014">
{{cite journal 
|last= Iorio
|first= Lorenzo
|authorlink = Lorenzo Iorio
|date=28 April 2014 
|title= A new type of misconduct in the field of the physical sciences: The case of the pseudonyms used by I. Ciufolini to anonymously criticize other people's works on arXiv
|journal= [[Journal of the Association for Information Science and Technology]]
|doi= 10.1002/asi.23238
}}
</ref><ref name="Discover 2014">
